asthmaControlLevelAnalysis

TY Lee

10/02/2021

Data

EBA data contains measurements of asthma control levels for 618 patients (74% are >= 18 years old). The measurements were taken every 3 months for a year. I follow the 2020 GINA guidelines to define asthma control level by using the four indicator variables: daily symptoms, nocturnal symptoms, inhaler use, and limited activities in the last 3 months (it is actually 4 weeks in the GINA guidelines) before each measurement. I add these indicators, and if they are zero, then the level is controlled. If it is less than 3, then it is partially controlled. If it is equal to 4, then it is uncontrolled. I treat the answer as a . Besides baseline age and sex, I also use information on the time since asthma diagnosis. At the moment I do not consider treatment nor whether a patient experienced an exacerbation in the last 3 months before the visit.

I excluded two patients whose asthma diagnosis dates were before they were born and three patients who had no asthma diagnosis dates.

The data is more or less balanced.

Age is distributed bimodally - one for pediatric patients and the other for adults. Given this observation and the fact that mechanisms could be different between pediatric and adults patients, I will divide the data into two (<18 years vs. >=18 years) and perform a subgroup analysis as well.

The time since asthma diagnosis variable is binned into three levels: < 5 years, 5-20 years, and 20+ years (if used on the original scale, it leads to convergence issues).

Modeling

I plan to use a mixed effects proportional ordinal logistic regression using the package \(\textit{ordinal}\). The model is: \[ \mbox{logit}(P(Y_i \leq j|X_i)) = \theta_j + X_i^\top \beta - u_i, ~\mbox{for } j=1,2, ~ \sum_{j}P(Y_i=j|X_i)=1, \] where \(\theta_j\) are the cut points or threshold parameters, \(X_i\) is the covariates for patient i, \(\beta\) is the corresponding parameters, and \(u_i \sim N(0,\sigma^2_u)\) are patient-specific random effects. I can compute the individual probability following, \[ P(Y_i=j) = P(Y_i\leq j) - P(Y_i \leq j-1), \] and the constraint that the probabilities add up to 1. This is NOT equivalent to a typical multinomial logistic regression. For the ordinal model without random effects, I am assuming there is a latent variable \(Y^* \in \mathbb{R}\) such that for level \(k\), \[ \begin{aligned} P(Y=k|X) &= P(\theta_{k-1} < Y^* \leq \theta_k |X)\\ &= P(\theta_{k-1} < X^\top \beta + u \leq \theta_k |X) \end{aligned} \]

Preliminary Analysis

It is important to check whether the assumption of proportional odds (PO) is supported by the data. While it is not a perfectly legitimate statistical test, I compare the fitted fixed effects ordinal model with the baseline multinomial counterpart by performing a log-likehood ratio test (not legitimate because these models are not nested but it seems it is a well-accepted practice. See pages 289-304 of the textbook on applied logistic regressions by Hosmer and Lemeshow, 2002).

For covariates, I will consider sex, age, interaction between sex and age, age squared, time since asthma diagnosis, and the exacerbation indicator. I will perform the PO test and assess the goodness-of-fit of ordinals models at the same time using surrogate residuals (continuous surrogate response variable that approximates the ordinal response variable; Liu and Zhang, JASA, 2018). I will consider two link functions: logit and probit.

formula1 <- as.formula("control_level ~ sex*age + age_sq + time_since_Dx + visit")

I was not able to fit a random effects multinomial model for pediatric patients using available packages (mblogit) in R (always ran into convergence issues). I was able to fit it in SAS using GLIMMIX.

Visual assessment of the PO assumption

I compute the estimated class probabilities for each patient, and then plot the probabilities against each categorical variable using color to stratify between the classes.

pred <-function(eta, theta, cat = 1:(length(theta)+1), inv.link = plogis)
{
  Theta <- c(-1e3, theta, 1e3)
  sapply(cat, function(j)
    inv.link(Theta[j+1] - eta) - inv.link(Theta[j] - eta) )
}


prediction_generator <- function(model,formula,dat,inv.link=plogis){
  design_matrix <- model.matrix(formula,data=dat)[,-1] # remove intercept
  beta <- model$beta
  design_matrix <- design_matrix[,match(names(beta),colnames(design_matrix))]
  re <- data.frame(studyid=unique(dat$studyid),re=model$ranef)
  dat <- dat %>% 
    left_join(re,by='studyid')
  lin <- (design_matrix %*% matrix(beta,nrow=length(beta))) + dat$re
  tmp <- pred(eta=lin,theta=model$Theta,inv.link=plogis)
  colnames(tmp) <- c("Controlled","Partially controlled","Uncontrolled")
  cbind(tmp,dat)
}

tmp <- prediction_generator(lm.ordinal.logit,formula1,df_all) %>%
